Successfully installed and configured Vercel Web Analytics for Next.js

## Changes Made

### 1. Installed @vercel/analytics package
- Ran `npm install @vercel/analytics` to add the analytics package
- Updated package.json to include @vercel/analytics as a dependency
- Updated package-lock.json with the new dependency tree

### 2. Updated app/layout.tsx
- Added import statement: `import { Analytics } from "@vercel/analytics/next";`
- Added `<Analytics />` component inside the `<body>` tag, after `<SpeedInsights />`
- The component is placed at the root layout level, ensuring analytics tracking across all pages

### 3. Verification
- Build completed successfully with `npm run build`
- All pages compiled without errors
- Linter ran successfully with no new errors introduced (only pre-existing warnings)
- The project structure uses App Router (app directory) as detected

## Implementation Details

The Analytics component was added following the App Router pattern:
- Imported from '@vercel/analytics/next' (optimized for Next.js)
- Placed inside the body tag in the root layout file
- Positioned after existing SpeedInsights component for consistency
- This ensures analytics tracking is enabled for all routes in the application

## Files Modified

1. **app/layout.tsx** - Added Analytics import and component
2. **package.json** - Added @vercel/analytics dependency
3. **package-lock.json** - Updated with dependency resolution

The implementation follows Next.js best practices and preserves all existing code structure.
